3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Drift calculates funding rates hourly using a time-weighted average price (TWAP) comparing the perpetual's vAMM price to Pyth Network's SOL spot oracle. The hybrid vAMM-DLOB model provides continuous liquidity while the JIT (Just-In-Time) auction system fills large orders at better prices. Funding payments occur automatically every hour at the top of each hour, with rates typically ranging from -0.01% to 0.05% depending on SOL market sentiment."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","SOL","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SOL/USDT on Drift benefits from Solana's ecosystem growth and high trading volumes, creating frequent funding rate imbalances. As Solana's native token, SOL experiences strong retail interest and institutional adoption, leading to persistent long bias and positive funding rates. The hourly payment frequency allows for more granular arbitrage strategies compared to traditional 8-hour funding cycles."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical SOL Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SOL funding rates on Drift have averaged 0.015% hourly during bullish periods, translating to approximately 131% annualized if maintained consistently. During major Solana ecosystem announcements or SOL ETF speculation, rates have spiked above 0.1% per hour. The token's correlation with broader DeFi adoption and Solana network usage creates predictable funding spikes during ecosystem upgrades and major dApp launches. Weekend rates tend to be lower due to reduced trading activity, offering potential entry points for long funding rate shorts."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities and Execution"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Drift's hourly funding creates 192 payment opportunities weekly compared to 21 on traditional exchanges, enabling more frequent rebalancing. The vAMM model ensures continuous liquidity even during volatile periods, though slippage increases during high network congestion. Cross-margining with other Drift perpetuals allows for portfolio-level funding optimization. JIT auctions can provide price improvements on larger arbitrage positions, but require timing coordination with the auction mechanism."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations and Network Dependencies"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Solana network outages pose the primary risk for SOL funding arbitrage on Drift, as positions cannot be managed during downtime. The exchange's insurance fund provides protection against liquidation gaps, but coverage may be limited during extreme market stress. Drift's liquidation mechanism uses a Dutch auction system that can result in larger losses than traditional order book exchanges. Cross-collateral features mean SOL positions can be liquidated based on overall portfolio health, requiring careful margin management across all holdings."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How does Drift's hourly funding compare to Binance's 8-hour SOL funding?","answer":"Drift's hourly SOL funding typically runs 10-15% higher on an annualized basis due to lower liquidity and Solana ecosystem enthusiasm. The more frequent payments allow for better risk management but require more active monitoring. Arbitrageurs often find better risk-adjusted returns despite the rate premium due to faster position adjustments."},{"question":"What happens to my SOL position during a Solana network outage?","answer":"Positions remain open during network outages but cannot be modified until the network recovers. Drift has implemented emergency shutdown procedures for extended outages. The protocol's on-chain nature means no centralized intervention is possible, making position sizing crucial given Solana's historical downtime events."},{"question":"Can I use SOL as collateral while shorting SOL perpetuals on Drift?","answer":"Yes, Drift allows SOL token deposits as collateral for shorting SOL perpetuals, creating a natural hedge against funding rate exposure. This eliminates spot market exposure while capturing funding payments. However, you'll need to maintain sufficient margin as SOL price increases could trigger liquidation on your short position."},{"question":"How does Drift's JIT auction system affect funding rate arbitrage timing?","answer":"JIT auctions occur for orders above certain size thresholds and can delay execution by up to 5 slots (~2 seconds). For funding rate arbitrage, this means large positions should be placed well before funding timestamps. The auction can provide better fill prices but reduces execution certainty for time-sensitive strategies near funding cutoffs."}]}]
